metadata.name: Plottable Thousands #7
metadata.description:
'Thousands' explores the packing of recursive circles and golden angle spirals distributing various particles on a A4 canvas.

A SVG file can be exported (right click save) to plot the piece physically.

You can enjoy the digital version that simulate ink effects and optional, thanks to the utility token decoupling, get a physical one: the digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their own materials and ship to collectors ‚Äì as long as NFT is owned at request time.

Code: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-thousands

@greweb ‚Äì 2022 ‚Äì tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM ‚Äì CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

metadata.name: Pobbles #221
metadata.description:
The pobbles are generative blob-rocks: staring in silence, sometimes half-smiling, generally bored. 

‚Ä¢ The pobbles are digital recreations of a series of rock-doodles by S.F.Kislev (my big brother). They are an attempt to capture a specific, singular handwriting, and evolve it using code. 
‚Ä¢ See the original, 2014 handmade version here - https://pobbles.tez.page..
‚Ä¢ Alternative titles considered include Peggles‚Ñ¢, Plops‚Ñ¢, Blobbies‚Ñ¢, Floofs‚Ñ¢, Flintstones‚Ñ¢, Lardies‚Ñ¢, Plumps‚Ñ¢, Fats‚Ñ¢ and Wet-Ones‚Ñ¢. 
‚Ä¢ The pobbles are written entirely in paper.js and p5.js. 
‚Ä¢ The pobbles are an effort to take generative art into the realm of the cute. 
‚Ä¢ They work well with toddlers.

metadata.name: Circles #164
metadata.description:
‚ÄúCircles‚Äù is a set of generative artwork make by sophisticatedly designed algorithm with surprising randomness. It explores different combinations of size, shape, color, arrangement, etc., trying to create different feeling about circles. 

I like circle because it‚Äôs a metaphor to the cycle of life, we start at one point and end at the same point. No matter the circle is big or small, thick or thinÔºåcolorful or dull, we experience it as a cycle.

Press the ‚Äôs‚Äô key to save the image to your computer.

metadata.name: Herbarium #744
metadata.description:
"Herbarium" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022

Occasionally, I stumble upon vintage scientific illustrations on various topics, exotically looking charts and graphs, alternative layouts for the periodic tables or psychological research diagrams, elaborate illustrations of botany and zoology, minerals, and natural and sometimes unnatural phenomena. Most of those illustrations are part of the "art and science" practices from the 18th and 19th centuries. At the core of those practices were observation and interpretation, unraveling complexity through visualizing abstract ideas or finding a creative approach for understanding previously incomprehensible forms. 

I'm an admirer of two female pioneers in the field. Maria Sibylla Merian created, with immense dedication, a book with intricate illustrations of plants and insects, later praised by scientists. On the other hand, Anna Atkins published a book with beautiful botanical cyanotypes, considered the first book with photographic images. These topics are the visual inspiration for pieces presented at ArtBasel HK. 

My mathematical background makes me naturally attracted to graphs, converting numbers to curves, and everything schematically displayed. Also, combining scientific symbols and illustrations with imaginary data inspires the spectator to find meaning in unrelated or random things or provokes latent skepticism towards assumed concepts of truth, reality, and knowledge.

metadata.name: Sirkel #55
metadata.description:
Sirkel is an exploration on circular shapes, grid and bold lines.
While the artwork is heavily dependant on the grid, the neighbouring elements can line up seamlessly. It‚Äôs a slight nod to op art mixed with minimalistic grid based designs.

- 3 different line weights
- 3 grid sizes
- 3 block styles
- 3 palettes + occasional dark version

Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save a 4096x4096px image.

metadata.name: indefinite parabola #56
metadata.description: The lines, starting from the main one, smoothly spread over the canvas, creating completely unique patterns. The essence of the art work is its uncertainty (as, for example, in quantum mechanics). As long as you don't mint, the parabola will point up and down at the same time. There is also a chance to get a straight line, complementing the uniqueness of the generation.

metadata.description: This project is intentionally released anonymously to emphasize the art rather than the artist. I hope you enjoy!

metadata.name: Unicorn #2298
metadata.description:
All of us have dreams, and everyone would like to meet a fairy, a genie, a wizard, or someone else who will make our dreams come true in a snap of a finger or with the wave of a wand. But we're the only ones who can do it. We are those magical unicorns, unique, inimitable, with our own qualities and magical abilities.
These unicorns are the visualization of our inner selves that makes our dreams come true. An embodiment of all the best with a huge positive magical power.

Twitter: @unicorn_nft_art
Web: https://unicorn-nft.web.app/

by @lucky26puch, @AgataBaranova17

metadata.name: Ex Mobius (Camouflage) #7
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender Renders.

Each output in this collection has the same "mobius" shape, but the number and positions of the colored regions varies.

All outputs in this collection will have the same color palette (called Camouflage).

Please allow up to 20 seconds for each image to fully load.

In live mode:
Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x1500px PNG.

Several "Ex Mobius" collections will be released, each with a different color palette.
